Author: jl777c#5810
Content: the problem with 1 to 2 seconds per trade, is that it will quickly saturate any blockchain that is being actively traded that way. remember blockchain space is a finite resource and each swap is doing the equivalent of exchange deposit, trade, exchange withdraw. compare the times on that basis and atomicDEX is very fast

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: if you want 1 to 2 second trades of imaginary crypto tokens that is on the CEX, then that is ok too. however, if you want to be actually trading the real crypto, you are limited by the blockchain speed and capacity

Author: Mark81#4505
Content: Also you have to take into account that depositing to CEX takes a lot of time too.

Author: Mark81#4505
Content: So in that way atomicdex is even faster!

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: this is why i am advocating the multichain approach to solving scaling, so we can have million tx/sec, but that creates another problem of terabytes of data that needs to be synced. i solve that scenario by the dual-daemon using codaprototol https://medium.com/@jameslee777/dual-daemon-chains-to-integrate-non-bitcoin-protocols-6d5b1b1f221

Author: Mr.Cryptodude#8986
Content: That is true, I have had to wait up to 3 hours after depositing to Binance. However it took  1 sec to receive coins in my AtomicDEX

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: fundamentally an atomic swap is a trustless tx on two blockchains, as opposed to a CEX that is a DB entry for funds that have been deposited that has to be withdrawn. Most of the CEX now require burdensome privacy invasion to withdraw your coins. if that is ok, then you can pretend to be trading the coins in 1 to 2 seconds and trust that you will be able to withdraw your coins.

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: From a maker point of view, trades takes a lot longer than a few seconds, even on CEX as they have to wait for someone to take their offer.

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: maybe having the trades taking more than a few seconds will lead to less panic based trades and more thoughtful trades? it would be fantastic if we can get the speed with all the other benefits, but without removing the blockchain throughput bottleneck and then the data storage/sync bottleneck, it seems we are stuck with the relatively slow atomic swaps.
